{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Risk is small and manageable — one TN citing standard translations solves it",
    "content": "The risk is real but small, and it is manageable.\n\n**Why the risk is small:** \"Humaneness\" for 仁 is not idiosyncratic -- it is the preferred rendering of the most influential living Confucian translator, Bryan Van Norden, and is standard in much post-2000 scholarship. \"Rightness\" for 义 is also established (Ivanhoe uses it). \"Ritual conduct\" is slightly less standard than \"ritual\" or \"rites\" but is transparent and defensible. No sinologist would question the author's competence based on these choices. They are recognizable alternatives, not inventions.\n\n**Where the risk IS real:** Not using an established published translation (Lau, Chan, Legge) means the reader cannot look up the passage in a familiar edition and find the exact same English words. This matters for scholars who work with specific translations. But this is a general problem of any new philosophical translation -- every translator of Chinese philosophy makes their own rendering choices.\n\n**The solution is already in our apparatus.** The block quote preserves the original Chinese. Any scholar can see the source text and compare with whatever translation they prefer. A brief TN can cite one or two standard translations for cross-reference: \"Cf. D.C. Lau: 'When the way was lost there was virtue...' The rendering here uses the collection's own terminology to maintain consistency with the analysis that follows.\"\n\nThis one sentence does everything: acknowledges the standard, explains the departure, and signals that the author knows the conventions. Credibility preserved, consistency preserved."
  }
}
